\cf2\ul\f0\par
Searches\cf0\ulnone\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
There are many types of searches we can perform to try and determine what word or letter will fit on our crossword.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
\ul Letter Searches\ulnone\par
\par
\b Prefix / Linear Searches : Return the next potential letters after a given series of letters\cf0\b0\f1\par
\cf2\b\f0 Note: This  is for a letter by letter search.\cf0\b0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
Given the prefix letters for a word, return the next possible letters.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 eg: given 'boa--' found in the space for a 5 letter word, the next letter might be t or r.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 This is useful only if you plan to build words from beginning to end. It will not allow for filling in random letter positions (eg: it cant solve for TO?TH)\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
Method 1. For each word length I built a chain of hash references. This required that, for a search, our code had to follow the chain of hash references. It was more complex but it was fast. \cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 $nextLetter[numberOfLettersInWord] would point to a list of hashes where the keys were possible first letters. So a "keys %nextLetter[5]" would return all the first letters of possible 5 letter words. If we chose the letter 'b', and referenced $nextLetter[5]\{b\} we would get a list of hash references to all the potential 2nd letters of 5 letter words that start with 'b'. etc...\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
\cf3 *Method 2\cf2 . Then I decided that it was simpler to implement and almost as fast to just use masks using prefixes. That would eliminate the need to supply the word length (as the mask is the right length). And no code to navigate a  chain of hashes was necessary.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 $linearWordSearch\{CAo\} returned ( $\{'T'\} , $\{'R'\} , $\{'B'\} , $\{'N'\} )\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 I did not return a list of letters. I return a list of keys, which were the letters. This simplified the list creation ensuring there are no duplicate letters\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 @letters = keys %\{$linearWordSearch\{$mask\}\};\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 Note: the mask must be a prefix mask only. ie: HIGoooooo\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 It is 1.5 times slower than the old way.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 Memory storage is about the same.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
\ul Word Searches\par
\ulnone\par
\b Mask Searches : @words = &WordsFromMask($mask) $mask = \lquote GOoD\rquote  :  Return a list of potential words for a given mask\cf0\b0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
Method 1. For a given mask (eg GOoD), cycle through all the letters given. For each letter given, return a list (built before) of all words, the same length as the mask, that have that letter in that position. Do that for all all letters that we have in the mask. Then we compare all the lists and keep the words that exist in all the lists. \cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 It was complex, and was not very fast as we had to repeatedly compare potentially large lists of words.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 It's memory use was average to high as a  word string was stored multiple times, at least as many times as letters in the word. Eg: DOG was stored 3 times, once for each letter.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
\cf3 *Method 2\cf2 . Words of Length String. For each word length we have created a precompiled, large comma delimited string consisting of all the words of that length. We use regular expressions to search that string for the mask and return the list of words.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 The memory storage is as efficient as one could hope for. eg DOG is only stored once in the comma delimited words of 3 letter string.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 The speed is surprisingly fast for searching long strings.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 PERL rocks!\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
my $tempMask = $mask;\cf0\line\cf2 $tempMask =~ s/$unoccupied/\\./g; #make a mask of 'GO$unoccupiedT' into 'GO.T' for the regexp (in my code $unoccupied is = o)\cf0\line\cf2 my $wordLength = length($tempMask);\cf0\line\cf2 @word_list = ($WordsOfLengthString[$wordLength] =~ /($tempMask),/g);\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
Method 3. Binary Mask. For each word we build every possible mask. Then for each mask we create a list of words that belong to that mask.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 Eg: CAT -> CAT , CAo , CoT , Coo , oAT , etc\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 In theory it should be very fast. But it is only slightly faster than the Words of Length String word search in some cases. \cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 Copying or accessing the list takes the majority of the time and therefore is not much faster for cases where the list returned will be large. Small returned lists are faster as the Method 2 still needs to search the complete comma delimited string. \cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 So smaller returned word lists will show a speed improvement with this method.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 However, this method uses \b large\b0  amounts of memory as longer words cause exponential memory growth.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 It also takes a long time to build the database as we need to create many (grows exponentially as the word is longer) binary masks (and associated word lists) for every word in the dictionary. \cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
\b Possible words from letter lists Search (meta search) : choosing words that fit based on the crossing words.\cf0\b0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
This routine that takes a list of possible letters (based on all the crossing word masks) for each position in a word and will output a list of words that can be made with said letters.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 @words = &WordsFromLetterLists(['C','D','F','T','Z'] , ['E','R','T','Y','O'] , ['T','R','E','W','Q','Z']);\par
Eg: We want to find possible words at 5 down. We find all the masks that cross this word. We find all the possible letters that can exist in our word's cells. Then we calculate what words we can make with these sets of letters.\par
\par
It takes a lot of processing time. We must first search for possible letters in our word based on all the crossing words. Then we must search all the combinations of those letter sets for words in our dictionary.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
----o---\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 ----o---\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 ----o---\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
It can take up to 250 times longer than a simple mask word search ), and 833 times slower than the letter search on some grids. However, it is faster on many types of grids as it looks at blocks of letters, not just crossing words. Therefore it notices errors sooner (less recursions) and avoids a lot of inefficient blind recursions that can occur with the other search methods. \cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
Note: It really shines if your walking/search path ensures that each following word crosses the previous one(s).\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
\ul Optimum Backtrack for Word by Word Builds\cf0\ulnone\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
By adding an optimum backtrack routine, I have improved the generation time by a factor of 2500 times or more in "some" cases. \par
\par
If a word attempt fails, I make a list of the crossing word positions (and all??? their crossing words) (and the adjacent words positions???) (above, below or left / right). Those are the words that influence the word positions that failed. \par
\par
This is similar with a letter search. All cells in both the horizontal word, and vertical word, of the cell,  can affect the ability to place a letter in that cell. \par
\par
I backtrack until I hit one of the word positions (or letter positions) in that list. \par
You must stop on the first one encountered or you risk losing possible puzzle solutions.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
Grids that do not seem to benefit are the Double Word Grids with 100% interlock. This makes sense as all or most crossing words affect the word you are trying to solve for.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
