\ul Dictionary and Clues\cf0\ulnone\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
For huge word lists (required for big grids) a combined dictionary and clue database list is huge. \cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
A single database of all words and clues is very large and takes too much time to load and organize the data logically.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
If we want our crossword algorithm to have quick access it must be loaded into RAM. But there are very few systems with that much RAM.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
I settled on creating text files based on word lengths. 3.txt contains all 3 letter words in the dictionary. 7.txt contains all the 7 letter words.\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0\par
After the crossword grid is loaded, only the required text files are loaded into a PERL array \kerning0 $wordsOfLengthString[$wordLength]. All the words in that array are comma delimited. Since PERL regular expression searches are amazingly fast, we can quickly search for word patterns to get the words we need to fit.\cf0\kerning1\f1\par
\cf2\kerning0\f0\par
Once the words are all placed in the puzzle and we need the clues for those words. A quick way to load clues would to have a word.txt file for each word containing all the possible clues. \cf0\kerning1\f1\par
\cf2\kerning0\f0\par
\kerning1 jude.txt would contain:\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 Name in a Beatles song\cf0\f1\par
\cf2\f0 Law of "Sleuth"\cf0\f1\par
